Mh, still cannot confirm. It works fine with me. Here is what I did.
- Used a new 'desktop' skeleton (named 'gui').
- Added your 'statics' section from above in the gui/Application.js class.
- Added this line to the "main" method: console.log("single (default: false): " + gui.Application.SINGLE);
- Added the necessary environment settings in config.json:
"build-script" :{ "environment" : { "qx.allowUrlSettings" : true, "com.colvir.PROXY" : "blah", "com.colvir.single": false // this is just to provide a different value as default, // to see the difference when set via URL } },
- Ran 'generate.py build'
- Opened the build version with http://localhost/.../build/?qxenv:com.colvir.single:true#
- The console shows "single (default: false): true". No further warnings or error messages.
You wrote your code hasn't been changed, but maybe the config.json?!
It would help if you reported which error exactly you are getting. Is the initialisation of the static members already a problem? Or only when you access their value from your code? If so, how do you access them?

Created attachment 1162 Test case
Unpack in dir, which contains qooxdoo dir.
Run generate.py and generate.py build
Run static.js (require node.js)
Visit these urls:
http://localhost:8888/source/?qxenv:uritest.hello:true http://localhost:8888/build/?qxenv:uritest.hello:true

Ah, now I'm getting at it. I can now reproduce what you mean. (The problem with my earlier test was that I was not using all optimizations when doing the build version and hence didn't get the effect; s.further).
The issue is the "variants" optimization in the build version. If an Environment.get() call is decidable at build time (due to information provided by the config), the call is replace by its value, so
VALUE: qx.core.Environment.get('uritest.hello')
is replaced by
VALUE: false
Consequently, the value of "uritest.hello" is never retrieved at runtime, even though the environment key has been correctly updated from the URL parameter. So in a way, qx.allowUrlSettings conflicts with "variants" optimization, as the latter one "burns in" the information from build time.
The reason for the change in behaviour with recent qooxdoo is that we have increased the number of code locations where qx.core.Environment calls are being optimized (earlier, that was only done in loop conditions).
You have now two options:
* Disable "variants" optimization That would solve the issue, but would probably also be overshooting as it deprives you from any other dead-code removal, e.g. of debug code (guarded by "qx.debug").
* Remove the setings you wish to override from the config If you remove the environment/uritest.hello key from config.json, the generator has nothing to optimize calls for that key, so the calls remain in the code and are evaluated at runtime. If you wish you can still provide a default value for this key, but rather in the class code either by adding an "environment" section to the class map, or add a call to qx.core.Environment.add("uritest.hello"... in the "defer" member. In any case this would be more specific to that particular key, and seems more appropriate.
I don't think there is a general solution for that. It is in a sense contradictory to instruct the generator to remove code by providing compile-time values for environment keys, and then wanting to override these values later. But I will add a warning to the generator to alert users if there is this conflict.

Add warning to generator if variants optimization and qx.allowUrlSettings are both in effect.
